studyDesigns.name: Study Design
studyDesigns.rationale: Protocol-defined study design for investigating efficacy and safety

arms.name: Dapagliflozin 10 mg
arms.description: Dapagliflozin 10 mg once daily in addition to background regional standard of care therapy. Dose may be temporarily reduced to 5 mg if clinically indicated.

arms.name: Placebo
arms.description: Matching placebo once daily in addition to background regional standard of care therapy.

studyCohorts.name: Type 2 Diabetes (T2D)
studyCohorts.characteristic: Patients with an established diagnosis of type 2 diabetes at randomisation (at least 30% of total population)

studyCohorts.name: Non-Diabetes
studyCohorts.characteristic: Patients without an established diagnosis of type 2 diabetes at randomisation (at least 30% of total population)

studyCohorts.name: Echocardiographic Sub-study
studyCohorts.characteristic: A subset of approximately 300-400 patients evaluating changes in cardiac structure and function

population.name: Study Population
population.description: Target population defined by eligibility criteria

objectives.name: Primary Objective
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin is superior to placebo, when added to standard of care, in reducing the incidence of CV death or a HF event (hospitalisation for HF or equivalent HF event, i.e., an urgent HF visit).

objectives.name: Secondary Objective 1
objectives.text: To compare the effect of dapagliflozin versus placebo on CV death or hospitalisation for HF.

objectives.name: Secondary Objective 2
objectives.text: To compare the effect of dapagliflozin versus placebo on total number of recurrent HF hospitalisations and CV death.

objectives.name: Secondary Objective 3
objectives.text: To compare the effect of treatment with dapagliflozin versus placebo on the Kansas City Cardiomyopathy Questionnaire (KCCQ) total symptom score for HF symptoms and physical limitations.

objectives.name: Secondary Objective 4
objectives.text: To determine if dapagliflozin compared with placebo reduces the incidence of a composite endpoint of worsening renal function.

objectives.name: Secondary Objective 5
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin, compared with placebo, reduces the incidence of all-cause mortality.

objectives.name: Safety Objective
objectives.text: To evaluate the safety and tolerability of dapagliflozin in this patient population.

objectives.name: Exploratory Objective 1
objectives.text: To compare the effect of dapagliflozin versus placebo on an expanded composite outcome reflecting worsening of HF.

objectives.name: Exploratory Objective 2
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin compared with placebo will have effect on New York Heart Association (NYHA) class.

objectives.name: Exploratory Objective 3
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin compared with placebo will reduce the incidence of diagnosis of atrial fibrillation (AF) in patients without history of AF at baseline.

objectives.name: Exploratory Objective 4
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin compared with placebo will result in a reduction of the incidence of hyper – and hypokalaemia.

objectives.name: Exploratory Objective 5
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin compared with placebo will affect the number of events of doubling of serum creatinine.

objectives.name: Exploratory Objective 6
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin compared with placebo will reduce the incidence of diagnosis of T2D in patients without diabetes at baseline.

objectives.name: Exploratory Objective 7
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin compared with placebo will have effect on HbA1c in T2D subgroup.

objectives.name: Exploratory Objective 8
objectives.text: To determine whether dapagliflozin compared with placebo will have an effect on systolic BP.

endpoints.name: Primary Outcome Measure
endpoints.text: Time to the first occurrence of any of the components of this composite: 1. CV death 2. Hospitalisation for HF 3. An urgent HF visit

endpoints.name: Secondary Outcome Measure 1
endpoints.text: Time to the first occurrence of either of the components of this composite: 1. CV death 2. Hospitalisation for HF

endpoints.name: Secondary Outcome Measure 2
endpoints.text: Total number of (first and recurrent) HF hospitalisations and CV death.

endpoints.name: Secondary Outcome Measure 3
endpoints.text: Change from baseline measured at 8 months in the total symptom score of the KCCQ, a specific HF patient reported outcome questionnaire.

endpoints.name: Secondary Outcome Measure 4
endpoints.text: Time to the first occurrence of any of the components of this composite: 1. ≥50% sustained* decline in eGFR 2. Reaching End Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) 3. Renal death

endpoints.name: Secondary Outcome Measure 5
endpoints.text: Time to death from any cause.

endpoints.name: Safety Outcome Measure 2
endpoints.text: Discontinuation of IP due to Adverse Events (DAEs)

endpoints.name: Safety Outcome Measure 4
endpoints.text: AEs of interest (volume depletion, renal events, major hypoglycaemic events, fractures, Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), AEs leading to amputation and AEs leading to a risk for lower limb amputations [“preceding events”])

endpoints.name: Exploratory Outcome Measure 1
endpoints.text: Time to the first occurrence of any of the components of the expanded composite worsening HF outcome: 1. CV death 2. Hospitalisation for HF 3. An urgent HF visit 4. Documented evidence of worsening HF symptoms/signs leading to initiation of a new treatment for HF sustained for at least 4 weeks or augmentation of existing oral therapy for HF (eg, increase in dose of diuretic) sustained for at least 4 weeks.

endpoints.name: Exploratory Outcome Measure 2
endpoints.text: Change in NYHA class from baseline.

endpoints.name: Exploratory Outcome Measure 3
endpoints.text: Proportion of patients without history of AF at baseline with a new diagnosis of AF during the study.

endpoints.name: Exploratory Outcome Measure 4
endpoints.text: Time to the first occurrence of each of any of the following central lab levels of serum potassium: >6.0 mmol/L, >5.5 mmol/L, <3.5 mmol/L, <3.0 mmol/L

endpoints.name: Exploratory Outcome Measure 5
endpoints.text: Number of events with doubling of serum creatinine (compared with the most recent laboratory measurement).

endpoints.name: Exploratory Outcome Measure 6
endpoints.text: Proportion of patients without T2D at baseline with a new diagnosis of T2D during the study.

endpoints.name: Exploratory Outcome Measure 8
endpoints.text: Change in systolic BP from baseline.

notes.text: a. Local laboratory assessment is optional and may be used to assess eligibility (according to local routine) of NT-proBNP. If used, the ICF need to be signed before the optional assessment starts.
b. LV assessments should be done if no assessment has been performed within 12 months prior to enrolment, or if the results of prior assessments are unavailable.

c. Only for patients in the echocardiography substudy: A baseline echocardiographic assessment will occur after eligibility is confirmed and prior to the randomization at visit 2. A follow up echocardiogram will occur at visit 6.

d. Central laboratory assessments include alkaline phosphatase (ALP), ALT, AST, bilirubin, blood urea nitrogen (BUN), creatinine (including eGFR assessment), haematocrit, haemoglobin (Hb), HbA1c, NT-proBNP, phosphate, potassium, and sodium, as specified in Table 2.
e. PK samples will be collected at visit 7.
f. PGIS, KCCQ, EQ-5D-5L will be filled in at visit 2,5,6,7 and every 12 months after visit 7, and at PTDV and SCV. PGIC will be filled in at the same visits, with exception of visit 2.

g. SAEs will be collected from the time of informed consent throughout the study until and including the patient’s last visit. Potential endpoints, DAEs, AEs leading to dose reduction and temporary interruptions and AEs of interest will be collected from randomisation throughout the study until and including the patient’s last visit.

j. Blood samples for potential future biomarker research will be collected at visit 2 and visit 7 and may be analysed at the discretion of AstraZeneca. The biomarker sampling is subject to separate approval/consent by the patient and is optional.
f. PGIS, KCCQ, EQ-5D-5L will be filled in at visit 2,5,6,7 and every 12 months after visit 7, and at PTDV and SCV. PGIC will be filled in at the same visits, with exception of visit 2.

executionTypes.rationale: Obtained once at the start of the study to allow participation.
Occurs specifically at Visit 2 (Day 0) to assign treatment.
Assessed at multiple visits to track changes in total symptom score.
Continuous monitoring and recording of events over the entire study duration.
Conditional workflow triggered by evaluation of volume status or acute worsening of heart failure.
Recorded in detail in the eCRF throughout the course of the study at scheduled intervals.
Protocol mandated laboratory values are systematically analyzed at scheduled study visits.
Scheduled procedures occurring at Visit 2 and Visit 6.

titles.text: Study to Evaluate the Effect of Dapagliflozin on the Incidence of Worsening Heart Failure or Cardiovascular Death in Patients with Chronic Heart Failure with Reduced Ejection Fraction

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Informed Consent
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Provision of signed informed consent prior to any study specific procedures

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Age Requirement
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Male or female, aged ≥18 years at the time of consent

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: HFrEF Diagnosis
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Established documented diagnosis of symptomatic HFrEF (New York Heart Association (NYHA) functional class II-IV), which has been present for at least 2 months and is optimally treated with pharmacological and/or device therapy, as indicated. NB: Patients in which additional pharmacological or device therapy is contemplated, or should be considered, must not be enrolled until therapy has been optimized and is stable for ≥1 month.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: LVEF Requirement
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) ≤40% (echocardiogram, radionuclide ventriculogram, contrast angiography or cardiac MRI ) within the last 12 months prior to enrolment (Visit 1): - If there is more than one assessment of LVEF the value from the most recent measurement should be used in assessing eligibility - Patients undergoing coronary revascularization (percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) or coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG)), valve repair/replacement or implantation of a cardiac resynchronization therapy (CRT) device or any other surgical, device or pharmacological intervention (ie initiation of a beta-blocker) that might improve LVEF must have a measurement of LVEF at least 3 months after the intervention in order to be eligible. NB: Patients with known HFrEF but without a recent (≤12 months) assessment of left ventricular (LV) function will undergo a local echocardiogram at the time of enrolment.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: NT-proBNP Levels
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: N-terminal pro b-type natriuretic peptide (NT-proBNP) >600 pg/ml (or if hospitalised for heart failure within the previous 12 months, NT-proBNP ≥400 pg/ml) at enrolment (visit 1). - If concomitant atrial fibrillation or atrial flutter at Visit 1, NT-proBNP must be ≥900 pg/ml (irrespective of history of heart failure hospitalisation)

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Standard of Care Therapy
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Patients should receive background standard of care for HFrEF and be treated according to locally recognized guidelines with both drugs and devices, as appropriate. Guideline-recommended medications should be used at recommended doses unless contraindicated or not tolerated. Therapy should have been individually optimized and stable for ≥4 weeks (this does not apply to diuretics – see NB below) before visit 1 and include (unless contraindicated or not tolerated): - an ACE inhibitor, or ARB or sacubitril/valsartan and - a beta-blocker and - if considered appropriate by the patient’s treating physician; a mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist (MRA). NB: Most patients with heart failure require treatment with a diuretic to control sodium and water retention leading to volume overload. It is recognized that diuretic dosing may be titrated to symptoms, signs, weight and other information and may thus vary. Each patient should, however, be treated with a diuretic regimen aimed at achieving optimal fluid/volume status for that individual.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: eGFR Requirement
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: eGFR ≥30 ml/min/1.73 m2 (CKD-EPI formula) at enrolment (visit 1)

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: SGLT2 Inhibitor Therapy
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Receiving therapy with an SGLT2 inhibitor within 8 weeks prior to enrolment or previous intolerance of an SGLT2 inhibitor

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Type 1 Diabetes
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Type 1 diabetes mellitus (T1D)

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Hypotension
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Symptomatic hypotension or systolic BP <95 mmHg at 2 out of 3 measurements either at visit 1 or visit 2.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Acute Decompensated HF
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Current acute decompensated HF or hospitalisation due to decompensated HF <4 weeks prior to enrolment

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Recent CV Events
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: MI, unstable angina, stroke or transient ischemic attack (TIA) within 12 weeks prior to enrolment

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Recent Revascularization
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Coronary revascularization (percutaneous coronary intervention [PCI] or coronary artery bypass grafting [CABG]) or valvular repair/replacement within 12 weeks prior to enrolment or planned to undergo any of these operations after randomisation

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: CRT Implantation
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Implantation of a CRT within 12 weeks prior to enrolment or intent to implant a CRT device

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Cardiac Transplant or VAD
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Previous cardiac transplantation or implantation of a ventricular assistance device (VAD) or similar device, or implantation expected after randomisation

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Specific Cardiomyopathies
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: HF due to restrictive cardiomyopathy, active myocarditis, constrictive pericarditis, hypertrophic (obstructive) cardiomyopathy or uncorrected primary valvular disease

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Bradycardia or Heart Block
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Symptomatic bradycardia or second or third degree heart block without a pacemaker

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Life Expectancy
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Any condition outside the CV and renal disease area, such as but not limited to malignancy, with a life expectancy of less than 2 years based on investigator´s clinical judgement

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Active Malignancy
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Active malignancy requiring treatment at the time of visit 1(with the exception of successfully treated basal cell or treated squamous cell carcinoma)

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Hepatic Impairment
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Hepatic impairment (aspartate transaminase [AST] or alanine transaminase [ALT] >3x the upper limit of normal [ULN]; or total bilirubin >2x ULN at time of enrolment). An isolated increase in bilirubin in patients with known Gilbert’s syndrome is not a reason for exclusion.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Blood-borne Diseases
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Known blood-borne diseases such as specified in Appendix B (category A and B)

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Severe Renal Disease
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Severe (eGFR <30 mL/min/1.73 m2 by CKD-EPI), unstable or rapidly progressing renal disease at the time of randomisation

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Contraception and Pregnancy
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Women of child-bearing potential (i.e., those who are not chemically or surgically sterilised or who are not post-menopausal) who are not willing to use a medically accepted method of contraception that is considered reliable in the judgment of the investigator, from the time of signing the informed consent throughout the study and 4 weeks thereafter, OR women who have a positive pregnancy test at enrolment or randomisation OR women who are breast-feeding

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Study Involvement
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Involvement in the planning and/or conduct of the study (applies to both AstraZeneca personnel and/or personnel at the study site)

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Previous Randomisation
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Previous randomisation in the present study

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Other Clinical Study
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Participation in another clinical study with an IP during the last month prior to enrolment

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Inability to Comply
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Inability of the patient, in the opinion of the investigator, to understand and/or comply with study medications, procedures and/or follow-up OR any conditions that, in the opinion of the investigator, may render the patient unable to complete the study. NB: Patients who cannot complete the electronic patient reported outcome (ePRO) assessments can still participate in the study.

studyInterventions.name: Dapagliflozin
studyInterventions.description: Highly selective and reversible inhibitor of human renal SGLT2 for the treatment of chronic heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF).

studyInterventions.name: Placebo
studyInterventions.description: Matching placebo tablets identical in size, color, smell, and taste to dapagliflozin.

studyInterventions.name: Standard of Care Therapy
studyInterventions.description: Regional standard of care for heart failure, including ACE inhibitors, ARBs, sacubitril/valsartan, beta-blockers, and MRAs.

studyInterventions.name: Diuretics
studyInterventions.description: Permitted and expected for volume control; doses may be titrated as clinically indicated.

studyInterventions.name: SGLT2 inhibitors (open-label)
studyInterventions.description: Prohibited in combination with IP; should be avoided during the course of the study.

studyInterventions.name: NSAIDs
studyInterventions.description: Use should be re-considered if unexpected acute decline in kidney function occurs.

amendments.name: Amendment 1.0
amendments.summary: Initial creation of the clinical study protocol.

amendments.name: Amendment 2.0
amendments.summary: The main reasons for preparation of this amendment were to expand the adverse event of interest category for amputations based on regulatory discussion, incorporate an Echocardiographic Sub-study, update secondary objectives regarding KCCQ scoring, and refine safety reporting procedures to simplify SAE reporting and minimize risks of withholding renal AEs. It also clarified exclusion criteria, contraceptive requirements, and guidelines for essential treatment during acute worsening of heart failure.

transitionRules.name: Screening to Randomization
transitionRules.text: Patients must meet all inclusion and no exclusion criteria; screen failures must not be randomised

transitionRules.name: Dose Reduction Trigger
transitionRules.text: If volume depletion, hypotension, or worsening kidney function do not resolve with other measures, reduce IP to 5 mg

transitionRules.name: Dose Escalation Trigger
transitionRules.text: Increase dose back to 10 mg as soon as the patient's condition is stable

transitionRules.name: Permanent Discontinuation for DKA
transitionRules.text: If Diabetic Ketoacidosis (DKA) is confirmed, IP should be discontinued permanently

commentAnnotations.text: Patients who cannot complete the electronic patient reported outcome (ePRO) assessments can still participate in the study
After stopping IP the investigator should ensure that the patient is treated according to standard clinical practice and ascertain there is a proper medical follow-up plan in place
Failure to meet the criteria for NT-proBNP is expected to be the main reason for screen failure in this study.

studyDefinitionDocumentVersions.description: Correcting typos, cross-references, adding Echocardiographic Sub-study, and expanding AE interest for amputations.

studyAmendmentImpacts.description: Changed KCCQ score reporting from clinical/overall to total symptom score.
Addition of an Echocardiographic Sub-study including objectives and procedures.

studyAmendmentImpacts.affectedSection: Section 2.3, 6.3.1, 6.3.2.6 - Safety Objectives and AE Collection
studyAmendmentImpacts.description: Expanded AE collection to include events preceding lower limb amputation.
Clarified exclusion criteria 3 and 13; extended contraceptive requirements for criterion 16.
Removed adjudication requirement for eGFR decline renal endpoints.
Limited event types withheld from health authority reporting to HF and fatal AEs only.

studyAmendmentReasons.reasonText: Discussion with regulatory authorities regarding lower limb amputation risks.
Feedback from regulatory authorities and harmonization with the Informed Consent Form (ICF).
Endpoint criteria did not justify the adjudication of eGFR decline events.
Simplify SAE reporting and minimize risk of incorrectly withholding renal AEs of interest.
Correcting typos, cross-references, and alignment with AstraZeneca House style.

studyChanges.summary: Updated the specific KCCQ score used for secondary variable analysis.
Added a new section to capture information related to the echocardiographic sub-study.

studyChanges.afterText: AEs leading to amputation and AEs leading to a risk for lower limb amputations (preceding events)
studyChanges.summary: Expanded safety reporting to include events that place a patient at risk for amputation.

studyChanges.beforeText: Requirement of adjudicating potential endpoints related to eGFR decline
studyChanges.summary: Eliminated the need for adjudication for specific renal decline endpoints.

studyChanges.afterText: Investigator responsibility regarding standard of care treatment after IP discontinuation
studyChanges.summary: Clarified post-IP treatment responsibilities for investigators.
